<h3>3. Peloton: Fitness Newbies</h3>
<p>Itâ€™s hard to think of a Peloton ad and not think of <em>the </em>Peloton ad. But this commercial takes a different tactic (and, well, a less problematic and less viral one).</p>
<p>Here, Peloton is appealing to those new to fitness and interested in establishing a routine, regardless of physical goals. Instead, this ad stresses that taking Peloton classes can be fun.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/RGv9hBLUteY?si=_4u3rI-yAkJd5YgP" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p>Here&#8217;s who we can infer theyâ€™re targeting:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Demographics: </strong>This is wider, but itâ€™s still limited to those who can afford to shell out more than $1,000 for a bike and $40 for a monthly subscription.</li>
<li><strong>Motivations: </strong>Trying something new, enjoying fitness, finding a routine that works, engaging in community.</li>
<li><strong>Pain points: </strong>Fitness programs that are solitary and intimidating.</li>
<li><strong>Marketing channels: </strong>TV, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/optimize-youtube-ad-campaigns">YouTube</a>, Facebook.</li>
</ul>
